performance_optimizations.description:
Add a bloom filter on valid customer keys (after c_mktsegment filter) to skip non-matching orders before hash table probe. Steps:

1. After filtering customers (valid_customers hash set with ~300K entries at SF10), build a bloom filter:
   - Size: 300K * 10 bits = 375KB (fits in L2 cache)
   - 3-4 hash functions
   - False positive rate: ~1%

2. During orders scan, check bloom filter BEFORE probing valid_customers hash set:
   ```cpp
   if (!customer_bloom.contains(orders.o_custkey[i])) {
       continue;  // Definitely not in customer set
   }
   if (valid_customers.find(orders.o_custkey[i]) != valid_customers.end()) {
       // Actual match
   }
   ```

3. Expected savings: Orders table has 15M rows, bloom filter eliminates 80% of non-matching probes (12M unnecessary hash lookups). Each lookup saved = 40ns (std::unordered_map) or 8ns (flat_hash_map). With flat_hash_map: 12M * 8ns = 96ms saved. With std::unordered_map: 480ms saved.

Important: This optimization has higher value if combined with Priority 1 (flat_hash_map). If keeping std::unordered_map, bloom filter saves more (480ms vs 96ms).

During the lineitem scan and probe phase (q3.cpp lines 106-120), hash table lookups into valid_orders are random access causing cache misses. Use software prefetching to hide latency:

```cpp
const size_t PREFETCH_DISTANCE = 8;

for (size_t i = block_start; i < block_end; i++) {
    // Prefetch 8 rows ahead
    if (i + PREFETCH_DISTANCE < block_end) {
        int32_t future_orderkey = lineitem.l_orderkey[i + PREFETCH_DISTANCE];
        // Prefetch the hash bucket for future lookup
        auto it_future = valid_orders.find(future_orderkey);
        __builtin_prefetch(&(*it_future), 0, 1);
    }

    // Process current row
    if (lineitem.l_shipdate[i] > ship_date_cutoff) {
        auto it = valid_orders.find(lineitem.l_orderkey[i]);
        // ... rest of logic
    }
}
```

Note: This is tricky to implement correctly with std::unordered_map (need to prefetch actual bucket, not iterator). Much easier with flat_hash_map where buckets are contiguous.

Alternative: Batch process in groups of 16-32 rows:
1. Collect orderkeys for 32 rows
2. Prefetch all 32 hash buckets
3. Process all 32 rows

Expected savings: 10-15% on the lineitem probe phase by overlapping computation with memory fetch.
